Binary Search is an efficient algorithm used for finding the location of a target element (or value) within a sorted array or list. It follows a divide and conquer strategy where the given sorted array is repeatedly divided into smaller halves until the target element is found or determined not to be present in the input array. Here's how you can implement Binary Search Algorithm:

1. Declare variables 'left' and 'right', which represent indices of the first and last elements of the given array respectively.
2. Set 'mid' variable as floor((left + right)/2), i.e., calculate middle index of the array.
3. If the middle element(arr[mid]) matches with our target element, then we have found it and return its position/index.
4. If the middle element is greater than our target element, then the left half of the remaining subarray contains our target element; update 'right' variable by setting it to mid-1.
5. Else, if the middle element is less than our target element, then the right half of the remaining subarray contains our target element; update 'left' variable by setting it to mid+1.
6. Repeat steps 3-5 till the target element is found or not present in the input array.

Here's sample Java code that implements the Binary Search Algorithm:

```java
public int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target){
    int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1; //Initialize Left and Right pointers
    while(left <= right){ // While loop continues till the left pointer does not exceed the right pointer
        int mid = (left + right) / 2; // Calculate Middle Index using Divide & Conquer approach

        if(target == arr[mid]){ // Checking whether Target Element is at MidIndex or Not
            return mid; // Return the Middle Index if Target Element is found
        }else if(target > arr[mid]){ // If Target Element is Greater than MidIndex, move towards Right Half
            left = mid + 1;
        }else{ // Otherwise, Target Element is Present in Left Half
            right = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    return -1; // If Target Element is not Found in Input Array, returns -1
}
```

